<li><a href="http://www.bartleby.com/61/43/I.html" class="external text" title="http://www.bartleby.com/61/43/I.html" rel="nofollow">AHD Definition of and usage note for <i>ironic</i></a></li>
<li><a href="http://etext.virginia.edu/cgi-local/DHI/ot2www-dhi?specfile=/texts/english/dhi/dhi.o2w&amp;act=text&amp;offset=&amp;query=irony&amp;tag=IRONY" class="external text" title="http://etext.virginia.edu/cgi-local/DHI/ot2www-dhi?specfile=/texts/english/dhi/dhi.o2w&amp;act=text&amp;offset=&amp;query=irony&amp;tag=IRONY" rel="nofollow">Extended discourse in <i>Dictionary of the History of Ideas</i></a></li>
<li>"<a href="http://afflatus.ucd.ie/sardonicus/tree.jsp" class="external text" title="http://afflatus.ucd.ie/sardonicus/tree.jsp" rel="nofollow">Sardonicus</a>"—a web-resource that provides access to similes, ironic and otherwise, harvested from the web.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.clown-enfant.com/leclown/eng/drama/livre.htm#IRO" class="external text" title="http://www.clown-enfant.com/leclown/eng/drama/livre.htm#IRO" rel="nofollow">Excerpt on dramatic irony from Yves Lavandier's Writing Drama</a></li>
</ul>
<p><span id="interwiki-lv-fa"></span></p>


